Delivery app

Core problem designed to solve
Chaos of Manual Coordination: It eliminates the daily stress and time wasted by sellers making endless phone calls and WhatsApp messages to find available riders and track parcel locations.
Cash-on-Delivery (COD) Delays: It solves the cash flow problem where riders delay remitting money collected from customers (Lipa ukiona bidhaa) or mix up the business's daily earnings with their own cash.
Lack of Accountability and Disputes: It stops the "he-said, she-said" arguments regarding lost, delayed, or damaged packages by introducing digital proof of delivery and clear status tracking.
Erratic and Unpredictable Pricing: It fixes the issue of riders arbitrarily changing delivery fees due to rain, traffic, or guesswork, providing flat, predictable pricing that sellers can pass on to their buyers.


Justification
Nairobi's booming social-commerce market is heavily choked by informal logistics. Small online sellers lose hours of productive time chasing riders, tracking deliveries over phone calls, and managing delayed Cash-on-Delivery remittances. This app digitizes the relationship between the e-commerce vendor and the delivery rider bringing predictable pricing, unified tracking, and financial security to the local peer-to-peer marketplace 


DATABASE AND TABLE CREATED

Table 1: users (The Sellers)
This table stores the authentication credentials and business details for the online merchants (Jiji, Instagram, Facebook sellers) who are sending the parcels.
id (SERIAL, Primary Key)
business_name (VARCHAR(100), Not Null)
contact_person (VARCHAR(100), Not Null)
email (VARCHAR(100), Unique, Not Null)
phone_number (VARCHAR(20), Unique, Not Null) — Crucial for M-Pesa tracking and communications
password (VARCHAR(255), Not Null) — Hashed password string
created_at (TIMESTAMP, Default NOW())
Table 2: riders
This table holds information about the Boda Boda riders who register on your platform to fulfill deliveries.
id (SERIAL, Primary Key)
full_name (VARCHAR(100), Not Null)
phone_number (VARCHAR(20), Unique, Not Null)
national_id (VARCHAR(20), Unique, Not Null) — Important for vetting, safety, and security
number_plate (VARCHAR(20), Unique, Not Null) — e.g., KMCE 123X
is_available (BOOLEAN, Default TRUE) — To check if they can accept a new gig
password (VARCHAR(255), Not Null)
created_at (TIMESTAMP, Default NOW())
Table 3: deliveries
The central transaction table. Every time a seller requests a dispatch, a row is created here to track the route and specifications.
id (SERIAL, Primary Key)
seller_id (INTEGER, Foreign Key referencing users(id) ON DELETE RESTRICT)
rider_id (INTEGER, Foreign Key referencing riders(id) ON DELETE SET NULL) — Null if a rider hasn't accepted yet
pickup_location (VARCHAR(255), Not Null) — e.g., CBD Kamukunji Trading Center
destination (VARCHAR(255), Not Null) — e.g., Ngong Road, Stage 4
customer_name (VARCHAR(100), Not Null)
customer_phone (VARCHAR(20), Not Null)
delivery_fee (NUMERIC(10,2), Not Null) — The calculated fixed fare for the rider
status (VARCHAR(50), Default 'Pending') — Can be: 'Pending', 'Assigned', 'Picked Up', 'In Transit', 'Delivered', 'Cancelled'
created_at (TIMESTAMP, Default NOW())
Table 4: payments (COD Tracking)
Because Cash-on-Delivery (COD) is vital for your app, this table tracks the money collected by the rider from the buyer, and its remittance status back to the seller.
id (SERIAL, Primary Key)
delivery_id (INTEGER, Foreign Key referencing deliveries(id) ON DELETE CASCADE)
item_cost (NUMERIC(10,2), Not Null) — The value of the Jiji item being sold
total_to_collect (NUMERIC(10,2), Not Null) — Item cost + delivery fee (if client pays delivery)
payment_status (VARCHAR(50), Default 'Unpaid') — 'Unpaid', 'Collected By Rider', 'Remitted To Seller'
mpesa_reference (VARCHAR(50), Unique, Nullable) — For validating payment receipts
remitted_at (TIMESTAMP, Nullable)
Table 5: delivery_logs (The History Timeline)
To prevent "he-said, she-said" disputes, this table tracks timestamps every time a delivery status changes, providing an audit trail.
id (SERIAL, Primary Key)
delivery_id (INTEGER, Foreign Key referencing deliveries(id) ON DELETE CASCADE)
old_status (VARCHAR(50))
new_status (VARCHAR(50))
updated_by_rider_id (INTEGER, Foreign Key referencing riders(id))
notes (TEXT, Nullable) — e.g., "Customer phone busy, waiting at the gate"
changed_at (TIMESTAMP, Default NOW())
